stylometry: A genetic algorithm takes an optimization model and analyzes it to find the optimum solution. First, it generates a population of numbers along the possible outcomes between the lower and upper bounds, and assigns these numbers with corresponding binary codes. Next, it creates a new generation of numbers moving away from the the first population to search for a better solution. The genetic algorithm continues until it does not improve over many consecutive generations. When this occurs, the genertic algorithm terminates, and this is called the stopping condition. Evolutionary solver is important and useful when solving nonlinear model problems because it always finds the global minimum or maximum. It also can extend beyond the size restraints of conventional solver. However, eveolutionary solver can take a very long time and it is beneficial to set a time limit for it to run.
